Certainly! Below is a complete HTML file that creates an A-Frame VR scene featuring a city at night with 10 skeleton spheres that chase the user. You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser that supports WebVR.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>VR City at Night</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; }
        a-scene { height: 100vh; }
        .skeleton { color: #ffffff; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky color="#000000"></a-sky>
        <a-light type="ambient" color="#888"></a-light>
        <a-light type="point" position="0 10 0" intensity="1"></a-light>

        <a-entity id="city" position="0 0 -10">
            <a-box position="-5 0 -5" depth="10" height="5" width="10" color="#333"></a-box>
            <a-box position="5 0 -5" depth="10" height="10" width="10" color="#444"></a-box>
            <a-box position="0 0 -10" depth="10" height="15" width="10" color="#555"></a-box>
            <a-box position="-10 0 -15" depth="10" height="8" width="10" color="#666"></a-box>
            <a-box position="10 0 -15" depth="10" height="12" width="10" color="#777"></a-box>
        </a-entity>

        <a-entity camera look-controls position="0 1.6 0"></a-entity>

        <script>
            const createSkeleton = (x, z) => {
                const skeleton = document.createElement('a-sphere');
                skeleton.setAttribute('class', 'skeleton');
                skeleton.setAttribute('radius', '0.5');
                skeleton.setAttribute('position', `${x} 0 ${z}`);
                skeleton.setAttribute('color', '#ffffff');
                skeleton.setAttribute('animation', 'property: position; to: ' + `${x} 0 -10;` + ' dir: alternate; dur: 2000; loop: true;');
                return skeleton;
            };

            const scene = document.querySelector('a-scene');
            for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
                const x = Math.random() * 20 - 10; // Random x position
                const z = Math.random() * -20; // Random z position (in front of the camera)
                const skeleton = createSkeleton(x, z);
                scene.appendChild(skeleton);
            }
        </script>
    </a-scene>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **A-Frame**: The scene is built using A-Frame, a web framework for building virtual reality experiences.
- **City**: The city is represented by several boxes with different heights and colors to simulate buildings.
- **Sky**: The sky is set to black to represent night.
- **Skeleton Spheres**: Ten skeleton spheres are created and animated to chase the user. They randomly spawn in front of the camera and move towards the user.
- **Camera**: The camera is positioned at a height of 1.6 meters, which is typical for a standing user.

You can modify the colors, positions, and other attributes as needed to customize your VR experience!
